In this example, you'll need to provide your own service account key JSON file and database URL. You'll also need to provide a UID for the user you want to make an admin.

2. Set up database rules
Once you have an admin account in place, you can set up rules in your Firebase database to restrict access to specific collections and documents. Here's an example of how you can set up rules to allow admins to create posts in a collection, while others can only read them:
```json
{
  "rules": {
    "posts": {
      "read": true,
      "write": "auth.token.admin === true",
      "$postId": {
        ".validate": "newData.hasChildren(['title', 'content'])",
        "title": {
          ".validate": "newData.isString() && newData.val().length <= 100"
        },
        "content": {
          ".validate": "newData.isString() && newData.val().length <= 1000"
        }
      }
    },
